"Singh S.N.","Exploring correlation between redox potential and other edaphic factors in field and laboratory conditions in relation to methane efflux",2001,"Environment International","27","4",,"265","274",,,10.1016/S0160-4120(01)00055-1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0034771860&partnerID=40&md5=04d029e51d6eefd1c0e2c66ab9bb7fb5","Environmental Science Division, National Botanical Research Institute, Rana Pratap Marg, Lucknow 226 001, India","Singh, S.N., Environmental Science Division, National Botanical Research Institute, Rana Pratap Marg, Lucknow 226 001, India","Methane is primarily a biogenic gas, which is implicated in global warming. Although its production in the anoxic conditions is regulated by several edaphic factors, aquatic macrophytes also influence methane emission by providing aerenchyma to act as chimney for CH4 transport from the sediment to troposphere, by releasing root exudates to the sediment to serve as substrate for methanogenic bacteria and by transporting atmospheric O2 to rhizosphere, which stimulates CH4 consumption. Among the edaphic factors, redox potential (Eh) is the most important, which largely determines the action of methanogenic bacteria. Hence, a study was undertaken first to find out the correlation between CH4 emission and edaphic factors in the field conditions and then to understand the relationship between Eh and other edaphic factors. The field studies revealed that natural wetlands were the major source of CH4 emission, and the vegetation plays an important role in CH4 emission from the water bodies. However, it was very difficult to establish a strong relationship between the CH4 emission and the edaphic factors in the field conditions due to other limiting factors and their constant fluctuations. In this connection, the laboratory experiments exhibited that soil temperature, pH, moisture regime and incubation period were negatively correlated with Eh, which determines the initiation of methanogenic process. However, organic carbon and the water regime over the soil surface did not show any impact on Eh in this study. © 2001 Elsevier Science Ltd. All rights reserved.","Edaphic factors; Methane efflux; Redox potential","Bacteria; Gas emissions; Global warming; Industrial laboratories; Redox reactions; Sediments; Troposphere; Vegetation; Wetlands; Redox potentials; Methane; carbon; methane; water; biogenic emission; biogeochemical cycle; methanogenic bacterium; redox potential; article; controlled study; gas transport; incubation time; laboratory; methanogenesis; moisture; oxidation reduction potential; pH; priority journal; soil; temperature; vegetation; wetland; Air Pollutants; Euryarchaeota; Fresh Water; Greenhouse Effect; India; Methane; Oxidation-Reduction; Soil; Soil Microbiology; Temperature",,"Air Pollutants; Methane, 74-82-8; Soil",,,,"Chanton, J.P., Crill, P., Barlett, K., Martens, C., Amazon capims (floating grass mats): A source of 13C enriched methane to the troposphere (1989) Geophys Res Lett, 16, pp. 799-802; Cicerone, R.J., Oremland, R.S., Biogeochemical aspects on atmospheric methane (1988) Global Biogeochem Cycles, 2, pp. 299-327; Connell, W.E., Patrick, W.H., Reduction of sulfate to sulfide in waterlogged soil (1969) Soil Soc Am Proc, 33, pp. 711-715; Crozier, C.R., DeLaune, R.D., Patrick, W.H., Methane production in Mississippi Deltaic Plain Wetland soils as a function of soil redox species (1994) Soil and Global Change, , Lal R, et al. editor. Chelsea, MI: Leuis Publishers; Czepiel, P.M., Crill, P.M., Harris, R.C., Environmental factors influencing the variability of CH4 oxidation in temperate zone soils (1995) J Geophys Res, 100, pp. 9359-9364; Dunfield, P., Knowles, R., Dumont, R., Moore, T.R., Methane production and consumption in temperate and subarctic peat soils: Response to temperature and pH (1993) Soil Biol Biochem, 25, pp. 321-326; Grünfeld, S., Brix, H., Methanogenesis and methane emissions: Effects of water table, substrate type 